(Introduction to Photosynthesis) Tj T*
() Tj T*
(Photosynthesis is the biological process by which plants,) Tj T*
(algae, and some bacteria convert light energy into chemical) Tj T*
(energy stored as glucose. This fundamental process sustains) Tj T*
(nearly all life on Earth by producing the oxygen we breathe) Tj T*
(and forming the base of most food webs.) Tj T*
() Tj T*
(The overall chemical equation for photosynthesis can be) Tj T*
(written as: 6 CO2 plus 6 H2O plus light energy yields) Tj T*
(glucose \(C6H12O6\) plus 6 O2. Carbon dioxide and water are) Tj T*
(the raw inputs; glucose and oxygen are the products.) Tj T*
() Tj T*
(Photosynthesis occurs primarily in chloroplasts, specialized) Tj T*
(organelles found in the cells of plant leaves. Chloroplasts) Tj T*
(contain chlorophyll, a green pigment that absorbs light) Tj T*
(energy most effectively in the red and blue portions of the) Tj T*
(visible spectrum.) Tj T*
() Tj T*
(Understanding photosynthesis is essential for biology) Tj T*
(students because it explains energy flow through ecosystems,) Tj T*
(the oxygen cycle, and the basis of agricultural productivity.) Tj T*
ET
endstream
endobj
