(The Two Stages of Photosynthesis) Tj T*
() Tj T*
(Photosynthesis proceeds in two interconnected stages: the) Tj T*
(light-dependent reactions and the Calvin cycle, also known) Tj T*
(as the light-independent reactions.) Tj T*
() Tj T*
(The light-dependent reactions occur in the thylakoid) Tj T*
(membranes of the chloroplast. Here, chlorophyll absorbs) Tj T*
(photons, which excites electrons that pass through an) Tj T*
(electron transport chain. This process splits water) Tj T*
(molecules, releases oxygen as a byproduct, and generates) Tj T*
(the energy-carrying molecules ATP and NADPH.) Tj T*
() Tj T*
(The Calvin cycle takes place in the stroma, the fluid-filled) Tj T*
(space surrounding the thylakoids. In this stage, the ATP and) Tj T*
(NADPH produced earlier are used to fix carbon dioxide into) Tj T*
(glucose. The enzyme RuBisCO catalyzes the first step of) Tj T*
(carbon fixation.) Tj T*
() Tj T*
(The two stages are tightly coupled: the light reactions) Tj T*
(supply chemical energy, and the Calvin cycle consumes it to) Tj T*
(build organic molecules. Neither stage can proceed without) Tj T*
(the other, though only the first stage requires light) Tj T*
(directly.) Tj T*
ET
endstream
endobj
